[1] India
Date: Wed, 15 Jun 2005 12:27:25 -0400 (EDT)
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Times of India, New Dehli, India, 15 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1143020.cms>

As many as 9 dengue cases (including one death) and 56 malaria cases were
reported in Pune district during the first 5 months of 2005.
This was disclosed by V H Mohite, assistant director, malaria and filaria
control, and S V Patil, district malaria officer, while addressing a news
conference on the occasion of anti-malaria month here on Wednesday.
Mohite stated that out of the 9 dengue cases, 4 were reported in Baramati,
3 in Pimpri Chinchwad (including one death) [the case fatality rate or CFR
is 1111 per 10 000 - Mod.RY] and one each in Purandar and Maval. He stated
that since 2001 there has been a steady decline in malaria cases in the
district, and only 211 cases were detected in 2004 as compared to 736 in
2001. However, incidents of dengue have increased with 83 cases found in
2004 as compared to 29 in 2002 when dengue was detected in the district.
Speaking about the preventive measures taken by the health department, S V
Patil said that door-to-door inspection was conducted in every village and
patients were given medicines on the spot. 35 malaria clinics and 3140
tablet distribution centres are operational in the district. As many as 42
laboratories in the district are equipped to test blood samples collected
by the health workers.
Starting this year [2005], the malaria control office has decided to spray
insecticides in villages only if there is an outbreak of malaria. "The
decision was taken to avoid unnecessary use of pesticides and prevent
pesticide resistance among mosquitoes", he explained.
He said that emphasis was also given to biological measures, especially the
use of guppy fish that eat mosquito larva. As many as 390 guppy fisheries
have been set up in rural areas in Pune and another 247 in urban areas.
Patil stated that medicated mosquito nets were distributed for free in 10
villages under a joint scheme of the state and union governments.
Patil stated that a special anti-malaria drive is being implemented in the
month of June all over the state so that precautionary measures were
undertaken before start of monsoon and the awareness level was high.
--
