[2] Australia
Date: Tue, 14 Jun 2005 16:46:00 +0200 (CEST)
From: Dr. Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: ABC Radio Australia, News 14 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://abc.net.au/ra/news/stories/s1392056.htm>

Australian quarantine authorities are on alert after a [type of] mosquito
which could potentially spread dengue fever to new parts of the country was
detected in the Torres Strait. The Asian Tiger mosquito is common in
Southeast Asia and Papua New Guinea and has been found on 10 islands in the
Strait, situated off Australia's northeastern coast.
The Australian Quarantine and Inspection Service is now monitoring traffic
to Thursday and Horn Islands, which are the region's transport hubs.
Entomologist James Walker says the mosquito can carry a number of diseases
so it is important it doesn't spread.
"Asian tiger mosquito has the biological capacity to live in much cooler
climates than some of the other dengue-carrying mosquitoes," he said. "So,
potentially it could survive in parts of Australia where previously we
haven't had a mosquito that can vector dengue fever."
--
