[5] Sri Lanka
Date: Wed, 15 Jun 2005 19:24:28 -0700 (PDT)
From: Ranjith De Alwis <ranjith_alwis@yahoo.com>

Following the the massive outbreak of Dengue in 2004, Sri Lankan Health
Officials have set up the National Dengue Control unit for the coordination
and smooth running of the dengue control program.
Several pilot projects on social mobilization and control activities are
being implemented in the high-risk areas under this unit.
Update for this year (2005)
---------------
Total cases (both suspected and confirmed) - 1404
Deaths - 6 (up to 13th June 2005)
Monthly breakdown
Jan 379
Feb 247
Mar 236
Apr 231
May 232
June(13th) 79
When compared with the [same period of 2004] we observe a 65 percent
reduction for the given period
High-Risk districts - Colombo, Gampaha, Kalutara, Kandy, Kurunegala,
Puttalam, Ratnapura
--
Ranjith De Alwis, Entomologist
National Dengue Control Program
Ministry of Health
Public Health Complex
Narahenpita
Colombo 05, Sri Lanka
<ranjith_alwis@yahoo.com>
[The case fatality rate (CFR) for dengue fever in the report from Yemen in
2005 is approximately 290 per 10 000. The cumulative 9 cases of dengue
fever in India is rather small, but the fatality rate is about 1111 per 10
000. For the same period, Sri Lanka has a CFR of 42.7. The CFR values (per
10 000) vary dramatically: 4.5 for Viet Nam, 20 for Thailand, and 320 for
Philippines. The above figures are derived from the current reports and the
previous update: 20050612.1635. - Mod.RY]
